If you&#x27;d like my suggestion. I&#x27;ve been quite annoyed with some of the &quot;odd&quot; or &quot;non-consistent&quot; ways for splitting long lines onto multiple lines (either on definitions, or plain calls to functions). Eventually, I did come up with a consistent way to do so. Have a look at below:<p><pre><code>    def OtherLongFunctionName(One,
      Two,
      Three
    ):
        print &quot;Does stuff&quot;

    def MyFunction(Param1,
      OtherParam,
      FooParam,
      EtcParam
    ):
        if ((Param1 * 1000) > 5000 &&
          OtherParam is not None &&
          len(FooParam) > 50
        ):
            new_instance_dict = {
              &quot;TestingFoo&quot;: Param1,
              &quot;NewFoo&quot;: OtherParam,
              &quot;LongFooBar&quot;: FooParam,
            }

        recursive = MyFunction(
          OtherLongFunctionName(
            Param1,
            OtherParam,
            FooParam
          )
        )
</code></pre>
It doesn&#x27;t comply to PEP8 due to the indentation of nested params and stuff on the new lines. PEP8 apparently wants them aligned with the opening/starting bracket. This looks horrible, and just right-aligns all your code into little columns. And doesn&#x27;t work very well with nested function calls.
